title: For Sale/Trade:  1966 Marlin Model 99M1 in great condition!! Pre Serial number
postcontent:
Edit: I have done more research on this missing serial number and I have learned this was manufactured in September of 1966 (two letter code on the barrel).  This was 2 years prior to the GCA of 1968.  I understand that in late 1967 Marlin started putting serial numbers on these little 22 rifles.  

This is the most beautiful Walnut stock I have ever seen on one of these little Marlins.

Marlin only made this gun a few years (1966-1978) as I understand. It was styled to resemble the US Army M1 carbine, with eighteen inch barrel, handguard, barrel band, nine shot magazine even with the end of the stock! This was prior to making the cheaper and widely popular model 60. This features a walnut stock VS the newer birch stock. It also has a brass feed tube instead of the steel one found on the model 60. 

This is a fun shooter and a cool piece of history!

I will only sell to a person legal to own this firearm. Must be of legal age and a Missouri resident. I will also provide a bill of sale showing I am the legal owner and it is not stolen. I will show you my ID, and ask you do the same.

Text or call for a faster response (for won seven) 379- seven ate ate ate.

title: For Sale:  Concealed Carry Course, March 18th
postcontent: This isn’t your typical concealed carry class where you sit indoors listening to instructors lecturing for hours. This is a 3 hour class, 2 hours of which are live fire exercises at a beautiful outdoor range nestled in the foothills north of Fort Collins. The first hour covers basic handgun operation, firearm safety, the concealed carry application process, local laws and related statutes, reciprocity, prohibited use of weapons, carry requirements and restrictions and implications of using deadly force. The live fire portion of the course focuses on utilizing your handgun by drawing from a concealed holster at a variety of situations emphasizing on form, technique and safety. You are required to bring a handgun, a concealed holster (shoulder, cross draw and small of back holsters are not allowed), a minimum of 100 rounds (factory loaded ammunition, no hand loads), several magazines or speed loaders are recommended, proper clothing to conceal your handgun, eye and ear protection, sun screen and water are also recommended. All firearms and ammunition are to be inspected by the instructor prior to usage at the range. This class meets the formal training requirements needed to apply for a Colorado Concealed Carry Permit. You must preregister and prepay 100% of the class fee one week prior to the course. Other courses are available including NRA Basic Pistol and NRA First Steps Pistol Orientation. To register and for further details go to ColoradoPistol.com or call John at REDACTED.
